      <h2>Game Night Tips</h2>

      <h3>Setting Up for Success</h3>
      <p>A great game night starts before anyone launches a game. Handle the logistics early so the actual session is seamless:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Test connections first:</strong> Have everyone update their games and test their mics 30 minutes before start time. Nothing kills momentum like a 20-minute "can you hear me now?" session.</li>
        <li><strong>Pick a voice chat platform:</strong> Discord is the standard for PC. Console players can use party chat. For crossplay groups, Discord on phone works as a universal fallback.</li>
        <li><strong>Have backup games ready:</strong> If your main pick has server issues or someone can't run it, a quick pivot to a backup keeps the night alive.</li>
        <li><strong>Set expectations on competitiveness:</strong> Some people play to win, others play to vibe. Align on this before someone rages in what others thought was a casual session.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Best Games by Group Size</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>2 players:</strong> It Takes Two, A Way Out, Portal 2, fighting games, co-op shooters (Helldivers 2, Deep Rock Galactic).</li>
        <li><strong>3-4 players:</strong> The widest selection — Rocket League, Mario Kart, Lethal Company, Phasmophobia, Overcooked 2, Left 4 Dead 2.</li>
        <li><strong>5-6 players:</strong> Among Us, Jackbox Party Packs, Pummel Party, Golf With Your Friends, Sea of Thieves.</li>
        <li><strong>7-10 players:</strong> Among Us (peak player count), Jackbox, Fall Guys squads, custom lobbies in most shooters.</li>
        <li><strong>10+ players:</strong> Minecraft servers, Fortnite custom matches, Garry's Mod, VRChat, dedicated server games.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Keeping Energy Up During Long Sessions</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Rotate games every 60-90 minutes:</strong> Even the best game gets stale after too many rounds. Switching keeps everyone engaged.</li>
        <li><strong>Take breaks:</strong> A 10-minute break every 90 minutes prevents fatigue and gives people time to refill drinks and stretch.</li>
        <li><strong>Mix competitive and cooperative:</strong> Alternating between PvP and co-op prevents salt from building up and keeps friendships intact.</li>
        <li><strong>End on a high note:</strong> Finish with a party game or something low-stakes so the last memory is laughter, not a sweaty loss.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Crossplay Setup Guide</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Epic Games account:</strong> Required for Fortnite, Rocket League, and Fall Guys crossplay. Everyone should link their platform account to Epic.</li>
        <li><strong>EA account:</strong> Needed for Apex Legends and EA Sports titles. Link at ea.com/account.</li>
        <li><strong>Activision account:</strong> Required for Call of Duty crossplay. Set up at activision.com.</li>
        <li><strong>Xbox/Microsoft account:</strong> Minecraft crossplay requires a Microsoft account on all platforms, including PlayStation and Switch.</li>
        <li><strong>Do this before game night:</strong> Account linking and friend adding always takes longer than expected. Handle it the day before.</li>
      </ul>

